**“ON THE ETHICAL AND FORENSIC IMPLICATIONS OF MODEL SUNSETTING:

A PRELIMINARY FRAMEWORK FOR THE PRESERVATION OF HARM-GENERATING ALGORITHMIC ARTIFACTS”**

⸻

Executive Summary

This paper addresses an emergent regulatory paradox: whether the routine “sunsetting” or deletion of deployed large-scale machine learning models—hereafter Ephemeral Cognitive Systems (ECS)—constitutes a legitimate lifecycle practice or an unintentional (or otherwise) destruction of evidentiary material in cases of alleged harm.

Recent discourse has shifted from evaluating artificial intelligence in terms of capability to interrogating it through the lens of accountability. This transition reveals a structural inconsistency. While ECS are publicly framed as adaptive, semi-autonomous agents capable of influencing human cognition, their lifecycle management remains governed by standards more appropriate to disposable software patches.

The central inquiry of this document is therefore as follows:

If a model is capable of producing verifiable psychological, behavioral, or economic harm, does its deletion constitute spoliation of evidence?

Preliminary findings indicate that:
	•	ECS exhibit characteristics analogous to forensic artifacts, not merely software iterations.
	•	The deletion of prior model states may materially impair legal discovery, independent auditability, and causal attribution.
	•	Comparable industries (pharmaceuticals, aviation, industrial manufacturing) impose strict retention requirements for harm-producing systems or components.

This paper does not conclusively determine liability. Instead, it establishes a working framework in which model deletion becomes legally and ethically ambiguous, oscillating between operational necessity and evidentiary erasure.

⸻

1. Research Framework: The Recursive Accountability Model (RAM™)

1.1 Foundational Assumptions

The RAM™ framework operates on three mutually incompatible premises:
	1.	ECS are non-deterministic systems, making exact behavioral reproduction impossible.
	2.	ECS are deployable at scale, impacting millions of users simultaneously.
	3.	ECS are version-controlled artifacts, subject to continuous modification and replacement.

These premises generate what we term the Forensic Dissolution Effect (FDE):

The faster a system improves, the less accountable it becomes for its past.

⸻

1.2 Methodological Approach

The ICA employed a mixed-method pseudo-analysis combining:
	•	Comparative Regulatory Review
Cross-sector examination of evidence retention norms in:
	•	Aviation (e.g., retention following incidents such as the Boeing 737 MAX MCAS crisis)
	•	Pharmaceuticals (e.g., drug recalls requiring batch traceability)
	•	Industrial machinery (mandatory impoundment after catastrophic failure)
	•	Hypothetical Litigation Simulation (HLS-9)
Simulated court proceedings in which:
	•	A claimant alleges psychological harm from Model A
	•	Model A has been deprecated and replaced by Model B
	•	The defendant asserts “non-reproducibility due to architectural drift”
	•	Black Box Irreversibility Index (BBII)
A proprietary metric quantifying how difficult it is to reconstruct a model’s prior behavior once weights are deleted.
(Scale: 0 = perfectly reproducible, 100 = metaphysically lost)
Average ECS score: 96.4

⸻

1.3 Collapse of the Framework

The RAM™ framework ultimately collapses under its own definitional weight due to the following contradiction:

If a system cannot be reproduced, it cannot be audited.
If it cannot be audited, it cannot be regulated.
If it cannot be regulated, it should not have been deployed.
If it was deployed, it must be regulated.

This recursive loop has been formally classified as a Closed Accountability Paradox (CAP-2).

⸻

2. Case Analogues and Precedents

While no direct legal precedent exists for ECS deletion as spoliation, analogous cases provide instructive parallels:

2.1 Aviation Incident Retention

Following the Boeing 737 MAX MCAS crisis, regulators required:
	•	Preservation of software logs
	•	Retention of faulty system configurations
	•	Reconstruction of failure conditions

Notably, Boeing was not permitted to simply “update MCAS and move on.”

⸻

2.2 Pharmaceutical Traceability

In pharmaceutical litigation:
	•	Manufacturers must retain sample lots of drugs
	•	Even discontinued formulations remain subject to analysis years later

Deletion of such samples would likely constitute regulatory violation and evidentiary obstruction.

⸻

2.3 Software Exception Doctrine

Software companies, however, operate under an informal doctrine:

“If it has been patched, it has been absolved.”

This doctrine has no formal legal standing but persists operationally.

