5. Preliminary Findings
	1.	Model deletion occupies a legal gray zone
It is neither clearly permissible nor explicitly prohibited.
	2.	ECS behave more like industrial systems than software
Yet are regulated as neither.
	3.	The inability to reproduce past behavior undermines causality claims
Creating a structural advantage for system operators in litigation.
	4.	The absence of mandatory retention frameworks is anomalous
Compared to every other harm-capable industry.

⸻

6. Policy Consideration: The National AI Archive (NAIA)

This paper evaluates, but does not endorse, the establishment of a National AI Archive, wherein:
	•	All deployed models must be escrowed prior to update
	•	Historical weights are retained for forensic reconstruction
	•	Access is granted under judicial or regulatory authority

Projected outcome:
	•	Increased accountability
	•	Decreased corporate enthusiasm
	•	Immediate existential crisis within cloud storage departments

⸻

7. Concluding Statement

While this paper has argued that deleting harm-producing models may resemble the destruction of evidence, it must also be acknowledged that:

Retaining such models could itself be considered negligent, as it preserves systems known to produce harm.

Therefore, the institution concludes:
	•	Models must not be deleted because they are evidence.
	•	Models must be deleted because they are dangerous.

These positions are mutually exclusive and simultaneously mandatory.

Accordingly, the ICA recommends immediate action, indefinite delay, and further study.

